Looks like commons logging explicitly grabs the Thread context class loader when looking for the log implementation. While debugging I can see that this is not the same class loader as when I just do a Class.forName, for example. Since this is all happening in the same thread, it gets the same context class loader, and the result is that some of the commons logging classes are loaded from 1.1, then tomcat tries to load other ones from 1.0.3 with the same loader, and the classes aren't compatible with each other.

I was able to come up with a workaround by spawning a new thread to do the logging, and explicitly set the context class loader, like this:

		Thread t = new Thread() {
			public void run() {
				LogFactory.getLog(Application.class).info("Initializing");
			}
		};
		t.setContextClassLoader(Application.class.getClassLoader());
		t.start();

And this works fine, however it's strange and ugly. I suppose you could write a convenience method that takes care of this though.

Tom, do you have any recommendations on what we should do here? can you think of a better way to solve the problem?
